This lot had 118 sensors to start off, 34 sensors were rejected for Mean WE thickness and Max thickness. In previous alignment it was decided that for insertion units we were going to accept 30 microns. The reasoning was that an extra 5 µm doesn’t impact insertion, and the <25 µm limit relates to sensitivity, not insertion. The lowest mean thickness observed is 15 µm, so accepting up to 30 µm keeps total variation in mean thickness within 15 µm.

Based on this, sensors with mean thickness between 10 µm and 30 µm will be passed, and uniformity will be excluded until optimization for 50 µm is complete. In terms of Max thickness, we are accepting anything below 40 microns.

Custom field (Conclusion):
Currently, evaluation is based only on mean thickness. Uniformity was optimized for 100 µm in Sprint 2006 and hasn’t been optimized for 50 µm. JB mentioned in the SEND chat that we can be flexible with uniformity, so it won’t be used as a pass/fail criterion for now.

In SR, when yields were low, we accepted anything under 30 µm. The reasoning was that an extra 5 µm doesn’t impact insertion, and the <25 µm limit relates to sensitivity, not insertion. The lowest mean thickness observed is 15 µm, so accepting up to 30 µm keeps total variation in mean thickness within 15 µm.

Based on this, sensors with mean thickness between 10 µm and 30 µm will be passed, and uniformity will be excluded until optimization for 50 µm is complete.
